        "text": "To [[distinguish]] n objects, we can [[label]] them by n binary sequences of length [log2 n] each. Shorter sequences would not do. How about [[tristinguishing]] n objects? In this problem we use ternary sequences for labeling and require that any three of these be different in one and the same coordinate. This is the simplest unsolved case of a problem known as [[Perfect Hashing]]. We give a non-existence bound for a similar problem on binary sequences. We also deal with related problems of [[Edge-Colorings in Graphs]]. It is shown that the minimum number of tricolorings needed to give every triangle of Kn all the three colors in at least one coloring is at most [log2 n ]."
